 system and the need to earn a living outside the bureaucracy meant that although this was not the first generation of Chinese to break with traditional ways of thinking, these students were the first generation of Chinese to live differently. Based on student publications, memoirs, and other writings found in this country and in China, the author describes their multifaceted experience of life in a foreign, modern environment, involving student associations, professional activities, racial discrimination, new forms of recreation and cultural expression, and, in the case of women students, the unique challenges they faced as females in two changing societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aChinese studentszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aChinesexEducation (Higher)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aReturned studentszChinavBiography. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478041440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804780414/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles